00:02:58.670 --> 00:03:03.000
So that all makes sense, but it's problematic
when Smith universalizes that observation

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:08.560
by claiming that as a matter of convenience,
every prudent man in every period of society

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:12.240
must naturally have endeavored to create money.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:15.900
Smith -- man of the enlightenment that he
was -- is positing that the creation of money

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:20.349
is part of human nature. Like, in the second
chapter of Wealth of Nations, Smith explicitly

00:03:20.349 --> 00:03:25.069
says that the division of labour is the, quote:
"consequence of a certain propensity in human

00:03:25.069 --> 00:03:29.190
nature ... to truck, barter, and exchange
one thing for another."

00:03:29.190 --> 00:03:35.069
But yet, no! Like, what made sense for eighteenth
century city and town dwellers like Adam Smith

00:03:35.069 --> 00:03:39.940
doesn't necessarily apply to like, all human
beings over the course of many millennia.

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.970
And if you don't believe me, you can just
