00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:36.220
Alright, let's go to the Thought Bubble.

00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:41.580
So, according to Graeber, barter was reserved
for trade between strangers, even enemies.

00:04:41.580 --> 00:04:46.220
For most of human history, humans lived in
small communities, and in those small communities,

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:51.449
most exchange took place using forms of credit.
Basically, when people know each other well,

00:04:51.449 --> 00:04:56.710
they're willing to trade with the future expectation
that what one gives today will be repaid at

00:04:56.710 --> 00:05:02.430
some future date with something of roughly
equivalent value. So in small, localized communities,

00:05:02.430 --> 00:05:06.610
everyone is in debt to everyone else, and
there's no real need of physical money, like

00:05:06.610 --> 00:05:10.790
coins, as a way of keeping a count, because,
you know, you remember when someone owes you

00:05:10.790 --> 00:05:12.979
forty barrels of beer, or whatever.

00:05:12.979 --> 00:05:17.479
We see this historically in the early civilizations
of the Fertile Crescent, where the basic monetary

00:05:17.479 --> 00:05:22.740
unit was the shekel, and one shekel's weight
in silver was the equivalent of a bushel of

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:27.150
barley. Money in Ancient Sumer was actually
created by bureaucrats in order to keep track

00:05:27.150 --> 00:05:31.910
of resources and move things back and forth
between departments. But that doesn't mean

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:37.260
that silver actually circulated freely. Graeber
writes: "While debts were calculated in silver,

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:39.610
they didn't have to be paid in silver."

00:05:39.610 --> 00:05:43.610
So while some people seem to think that money
is naturally backed by precious metals, usually

00:05:43.610 --> 00:05:47.310
gold or silver, that doesn't seem to have
been the case. It was enough to establish

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:52.500
that something was worth a shekel or a fraction
thereof, and then trade for something of equivalent

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:57.639
value -- meat, or whatever else, without actually
having to have the shekels change hands.

00:05:57.639 --> 00:06:01.570
And this was especially helpful in economies
where taxes and payments to workers were both

00:06:01.570 --> 00:06:03.500
in grain, rather than money.

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:07.750
Thanks, Thought Bubble. So, first, Graeber
blows our minds by telling us that Adam Smith

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:13.290
was all wrong about money evolving from barter
societies, but what about credit as the precursor

00:06:13.290 --> 00:06:13.919
to money?

00:06:13.919 --> 00:06:17.250
I mean, it's basically saying that credit
cards aren't an advancement so much as they're

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:22.290
a return to the glorious past, except instead
of trust, there are like, large, faceless

00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:23.960
corporations with the power to sue you.

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:28.490
So the essence of credit is debt, and at least
according to Graeber, that's the glue that

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:33.310
holds social orders together, at least, if
you consider debt at its heart, to be about

00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:37.520
obligation. At least one of the things that
binds us together as a community is the recognition

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:42.460
that we owe our neighbors something and that
they owe something to us in return. It's like

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:46.610
keeping your lawn mowed so that you can keep
your neighbor's property value high. It doesn't

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:51.150
make sense to have a lawn -- they're expensive
and time consuming, and you can't eat grass.

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:55.139
But you take care of your lawn for the same
reason your neighbors take care of theirs.

00:06:55.139 --> 00:06:57.000
Out of the sense of mutual obligation.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.350
But money changes our understanding of those
obligations, right? Because once we're able

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:06.410
to put a price on our obligations, we can
make them transferable, which wouldn't be

00:07:06.410 --> 00:07:10.570
possible without money. Like, for instance,
it allows you to hire someone to mow your

00:07:10.570 --> 00:07:15.470
lawn for you, but Graeber argues that money,
especially in the form of coinage, also may

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:17.050
chattel slavery, possibly.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:21.460
So in West African social orders before the
arrival of Europeans, money was used, but

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:26.889
only for weddings, funerals, and other activities
that like, cemented human relationships. And

00:07:26.889 --> 00:07:31.630
the money largely had symbolic value. But
when Europeans arrived, they introduced monetized

00:07:31.630 --> 00:07:35.690
trade into the system, and in the process,
transformed that system. Money was no longer

00:07:35.690 --> 00:07:40.570
about transferring value to solidify relationships
between individuals and families; it was about

00:07:40.570 --> 00:07:43.370
quantifying debt and also making it transferable.

00:07:43.370 --> 00:07:48.479
So, Graeber's theory links money as we know
it to slavery and war, like, coins began to

00:07:48.479 --> 00:07:54.490
be used in India, China, and the soon to be
Persian province of Lydia, almost simultaneously,

00:07:54.490 --> 00:07:59.160
all around 600 BCE. And in Graeber's view,
this happened because this was a period of

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:04.210
time that saw a shift from earlier forms of
honor-based warfare, like, what is described

00:08:04.210 --> 00:08:08.229
in the Iliad, to a new, more state-based warfare.

00:08:08.229 --> 00:08:12.580
Armies started fighting over things like territory
and resources, rather than, like, kidnapped

00:08:12.580 --> 00:08:15.900
wives. So in a-- oh, it's time for the open
letter!

