00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:33.060
warfare.

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:37.620
Dear Honor-Based Warfare, um, I guess now
is the time in the video that I have to tell

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:43.180
you that I don't entirely agree with Mr. Graeber.
Like, with the Iliad we were telling ourselves

00:08:43.180 --> 00:08:48.660
a story about why we went to war, right? We
went to war not for resources, but for glory.

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:54.120
Honor. Now, I don't want to sound cynical
and disbelieving, but we still tell ourselves

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:58.230
those stories. These days, the President rarely
goes on TV and says, "You know why we're going

00:08:58.230 --> 00:09:04.520
to go to war? We need resources." No, we still
say it's about honor and ideas and standing

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:08.560
up for the defenseless, and et cetera, which
is all about as historically convincing as

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:14.370
the Iliad. In short, honor-based warfare,
I'm not entirely convinced that you, you know,

00:09:14.370 --> 00:09:17.140
exist. Best wishes, John Green.

00:09:17.140 --> 00:09:20.410
Anyway, so in all three of these governments
in India, China, and Lydia, they were pretty

00:09:20.410 --> 00:09:25.149
small scale, especially compared to the empires
that would soon come, but they built their

00:09:25.149 --> 00:09:31.080
power on professional armies that needed to
be paid, and coins were a great way to pay

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:34.820
them. It just works much better than like,
trying to split up the plunder among everybody.

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:38.980
The plundering method of payment is just like
a garage sale. The people who get there early

00:09:38.980 --> 00:09:42.740
get all the good plunder, and then the rest
of the people, they're just left dividing

00:09:42.740 --> 00:09:44.680
up, you know, old clothes.

00:09:44.680 --> 00:09:49.170
Also, in Graeber's view, states began to encourage
the use of coins because of the uncertainty

00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:53.980
of war -- like, violence creates uncertainty
for merchants, and decreases the likelihood

00:09:53.980 --> 00:09:58.350
that they will accept payment in the form
of some kind of trust-based credit arrangement.

00:09:58.350 --> 00:10:02.570
And soldiers aren't known for accepting credit
as payment, either, because, you know, soldiers

00:10:02.570 --> 00:10:06.290
are keenly aware that they might die soon.
So, according to Graeber, this combination

00:10:06.290 --> 00:10:10.970
of war and state-building led to the rise
of coinage. And then in order to keep paying

00:10:10.970 --> 00:10:15.430
soldiers, rulers, like, say, Alexander the
Great, needed to continue their conquests.

00:10:15.430 --> 00:10:19.830
So you need an army in order to have an empire,
and your army only likes to be paid in coins.

00:10:19.830 --> 00:10:24.360
Now, you can seize some sweet, sweet metal
plunder and then melt it down and make coins,

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:28.110
but with an empire-sized army, that's not
gonna cut it. You need more silver. Where

00:10:28.110 --> 00:10:32.850
are you gonna get new silver? Mining. Nope,
Stan, not miming, I said "mining", don't ever

00:10:32.850 --> 00:10:34.570
put mimes in Crash Course again.

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:38.560
So now you need a steady supply of miners;
fortunately, you've conquered a bunch of people,

00:10:38.560 --> 00:10:42.490
so you have lots of prisoners of war, and
now you have slavery.

00:10:42.490 --> 00:10:47.330
This military-coinage slavery complex was
described explicitly in the Arthashastra,

00:10:47.330 --> 00:10:51.890
a political guidebook written by Minister
Kautilya for the Mauryan dynasty, that made

00:10:51.890 --> 00:10:57.899
it clear that coins and markets sprung up,
above all, to feed the machinery of war. He

00:10:57.899 --> 00:11:03.140
wrote: "The treasury is based upon mining,
the army upon the treasury; he who has the

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:05.740
army and the treasury may conquer the earth."

00:11:05.740 --> 00:11:10.250
And Graeber says that China followed a similar
pattern: he writes, "The same fractured political

00:11:10.250 --> 00:11:16.019
landscape, the same rise of trained, professional
armies, and the creation of coined money largely

00:11:16.019 --> 00:11:20.390
in order to pay them." So, if money is a creation
of the state and its military, then it follows

00:11:20.390 --> 00:11:25.540
that when the state fails, as it did in Europe
after the fall of the Western Roman Empire,

00:11:25.540 --> 00:11:29.630
coinage largely disappears. And that's exactly
what happened, actually, but of course, that

00:11:29.630 --> 00:11:34.279
doesn't mean that transactions failed to take
place or that trade completely disappears,

00:11:34.279 --> 00:11:38.269
but it did decline a lot. And in situations
like that, people often revert to the virtual

00:11:38.269 --> 00:11:42.940
credit systems that we talked about earlier:
the ones that rely more on personal connections

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:44.800
than on like, state enforcement.

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:50.070
So Adam Smith's origin myth of money -- that
it derives from people's natural desire to

00:11:50.070 --> 00:11:55.600
make barter more convenient through the creation
of a medium of exchange -- really doesn't

00:11:55.600 --> 00:12:00.110
hold up to scrutiny. I mean, there are clearly
examples of an alternate history where production

00:12:00.110 --> 00:12:05.570
and exchange work okay without actual coins
or bills changing hands. It's kind of like

00:12:05.570 --> 00:12:10.660
today, actually -- money works as long as
there is some form of trust and a way to make

00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:14.610
people meet their obligations. People used
to feel obligated because failure to meet

00:12:14.610 --> 00:12:18.899
their obligations would hurt their standing
in their small, localized communities, and

00:12:18.899 --> 00:12:22.790
now we meet our obligations because otherwise,
like, people take our houses or whatever.

00:12:22.790 --> 00:12:27.180
But while we have evidence that money, as
we conceive of it today, isn't necessary for

00:12:27.180 --> 00:12:32.130
exchange, it IS necessary, or, at least, very
useful, for states, and I think states are

00:12:32.130 --> 00:12:33.180
probably good.

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:36.890
Oh, maybe not, I'm not positive. I just like
the internet so much; I don't think we would

00:12:36.890 --> 00:12:38.310
have the internet without states.

00:12:38.310 --> 00:12:42.519
So I wanna be clear that I don't entirely
buy Graeber's version of history. I might

00:12:42.519 --> 00:12:46.790
be wrong, of course, but I'm not convinced
that coins necessarily lead to slavery. And

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:50.339
I don't think that ancient slavery is really
comparable to the chattel slavery that we

00:12:50.339 --> 00:12:54.250
saw in the Americas. But I do think that it's
important to look at alternative points of

00:12:54.250 --> 00:12:57.910
view when it comes to history, even when you
don't agree with them. It's helpful to understand

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:01.660
that there's more than one well-argued point
of view in the world. And I do think Graeber

00:13:01.660 --> 00:13:07.240
very effectively challenges the idea that
human beings are like natural, rational, economic

00:13:07.240 --> 00:13:12.250
actors who wouldn't be possible without money.
And in the face of overwhelming anthropological

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:17.470
evidence, at least this much is true: money
is not the product of human nature; it's the

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:21.720
product of human actions, like the formation
of governments and markets.

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:26.040
In short, and I know this will disappoint
